      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\displaystyle A=A(\zeta ,\omega )=\operatorname {sign} \left({\frac {-\sin \varphi }{2\zeta \omega }}\right){\frac {1}{\sqrt {(1-\omega ^{2})^{2}+(2\zeta \omega )^{2}}}}.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/c6b2d0b2aacf605ceb7e12d45308023840342d41" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -3.171ex; width:52.881ex; height:6.843ex;" alt="{\displaystyle A=A(\zeta ,\omega )=\operatorname {sign} \left({\frac {-\sin \varphi }{2\zeta \omega }}\right){\frac {1}{\sqrt {(1-\omega ^{2})^{2}+(2\zeta \omega )^{2}}}}.}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>Compare this result with the theory section on <a href="/wiki/Resonance" title="Resonance">resonance</a>, as well as the "magnitude part" of the <a href="/wiki/RLC_circuit" title="RLC circuit">RLC circuit</a>. This amplitude function is particularly important in the analysis and understanding of the <a href="/wiki/Frequency_response" title="Frequency response">frequency response</a> of second-order systems.
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Phase_part">Phase part</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Harmonic_oscillator&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Phase part">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>To solve for <i>φ</i>, divide both equations to get
</p>
<dl><dd><span class="mwe-math-element"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext="{\displaystyle \tan \varphi =-{\frac {2\zeta \omega }{1-\omega ^{2}}}={\frac {2\zeta \omega }{\omega ^{2}-1}}\Rightarrow \varphi \equiv \varphi (\zeta ,\omega )=\arctan \left({\frac {2\zeta \omega }{\omega ^{2}-1}}\right)+n\pi .}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0">
        <mi>tan</mi>
        <mo>⁡<!-- ⁡ --></mo>
        <mi>φ<!-- φ --></mi>
        <mo>=</mo>
        <mo>−<!-- − --></mo>
        <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mrow>
              <mn>2</mn>
              <mi>ζ<!-- ζ --></mi>
              <mi>ω<!-- ω --></mi>
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              <mn>1</mn>
              <mo>−<!-- − --></mo>
              <msup>
                <mi>ω<!-- ω --></mi>
                <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <mn>2</mn>
                </mrow>
              </msup>
            </mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=</mo>
        <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mrow>
              <mn>2</mn>
              <mi>ζ<!-- ζ --></mi>
              <mi>ω<!-- ω --></mi>
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              <msup>
                <mi>ω<!-- ω --></mi>
                <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <mn>2</mn>
                </mrow>
              </msup>
              <mo>−<!-- − --></mo>
              <mn>1</mn>
            </mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mo stretchy="false">⇒<!-- ⇒ --></mo>
        <mi>φ<!-- φ --></mi>
        <mo>≡<!-- ≡ --></mo>
        <mi>φ<!-- φ --></mi>
        <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
        <mi>ζ<!-- ζ --></mi>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mi>ω<!-- ω --></mi>
        <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
        <mo>=</mo>
        <mi>arctan</mi>
        <mo>⁡<!-- ⁡ --></mo>
        <mrow>
          <mo>(</mo>
          <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mfrac>
              <mrow>
                <mn>2</mn>
                <mi>ζ<!-- ζ --></mi>
                <mi>ω<!-- ω --></mi>
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                <msup>
                  <mi>ω<!-- ω --></mi>
                  <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                    <mn>2</mn>
                  </mrow>
                </msup>
                <mo>−<!-- − --></mo>
                <mn>1</mn>
              </mrow>
            </mfrac>
          </mrow>
          <mo>)</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <mi>n</mi>
        <mi>π<!-- π --></mi>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \tan \varphi =-{\frac {2\zeta \omega }{1-\omega ^{2}}}={\frac {2\zeta \omega }{\omega ^{2}-1}}\Rightarrow \varphi \equiv \varphi (\zeta ,\omega )=\arctan \left({\frac {2\zeta \omega }{\omega ^{2}-1}}\right)+n\pi .}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/c8a82c46ba8a96338cdc9871279d5113b9b8e978" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -2.505ex; width:69.626ex; height:6.176ex;" alt="{\displaystyle \tan \varphi =-{\frac {2\zeta \omega }{1-\omega ^{2}}}={\frac {2\zeta \omega }{\omega ^{2}-1}}\Rightarrow \varphi \equiv \varphi (\zeta ,\omega )=\arctan \left({\frac {2\zeta \omega }{\omega ^{2}-1}}\right)+n\pi .}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>This phase function is particularly important in the analysis and understanding of the <a href="/wiki/Frequency_response" title="Frequency response">frequency response</a> of second-order systems.
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Full_solution">Full solution</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Harmonic_oscillator&amp;action=edit&amp;section=12" title="Edit section: Full solution">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Combining the amplitude and phase portions results in the steady-state solution
</p>
<dl><dd><span class="mwe-math-element"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext="{\displaystyle \,\!q_{s}(\tau )=A(\zeta ,\omega )\cos(\omega \tau +\varphi (\zeta ,\omega ))=A\cos(\omega \tau +\varphi ).}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0">
        <mspace width="thinmathspace"></mspace>
        <mspace width="negativethinmathspace"></mspace>
        <msub>
          <mi>q</mi>
          <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>s</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
        <mi>τ<!-- τ --></mi>
        <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
        <mo>=</mo>
        <mi>A</mi>
        <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
        <mi>ζ<!-- ζ --></mi>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mi>ω<!-- ω --></mi>
        <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
        <mi>cos</mi>
        <mo>⁡<!-- ⁡ --></mo>
        <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
        <mi>ω<!-- ω --></mi>
        <mi>τ<!-- τ --></mi>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <mi>φ<!-- φ --></mi>
        <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
        <mi>ζ<!-- ζ --></mi>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mi>ω<!-- ω --></mi>
        <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
        <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
        <mo>=</mo>
        <mi>A</mi>
        <mi>cos</mi>
        <mo>⁡<!-- ⁡ --></mo>
        <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
        <mi>ω<!-- ω --></mi>
        <mi>τ<!-- τ --></mi>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <mi>φ<!-- φ --></mi>
        <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \,\!q_{s}(\tau )=A(\zeta ,\omega )\cos(\omega \tau +\varphi (\zeta ,\omega ))=A\cos(\omega \tau +\varphi ).}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/4857b0dd875bf76c75551e1bac31a5b4680f298f" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -0.838ex; width:50.781ex; height:2.843ex;" alt="{\displaystyle \,\!q_{s}(\tau )=A(\zeta ,\omega )\cos(\omega \tau +\varphi (\zeta ,\omega ))=A\cos(\omega \tau +\varphi ).}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>The solution of original universal oscillator equation is a <a href="/wiki/Superposition_principle" title="Superposition principle">superposition</a> (sum) of the transient and steady-state solutions
</p>
<dl><dd><span class="mwe-math-element"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext="{\displaystyle \,\!q(\tau )=q_{t}(\tau )+q_{s}(\tau ).}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0">
        <mspace width="thinmathspace"></mspace>
        <mspace width="negativethinmathspace"></mspace>
        <mi>q</mi>
        <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
        <mi>τ<!-- τ --></mi>
        <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
        <mo>=</mo>
        <msub>
          <mi>q</mi>
          <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>t</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
        <mi>τ<!-- τ --></mi>
        <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <msub>
          <mi>q</mi>
          <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>s</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
        <mi>τ<!-- τ --></mi>
        <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \,\!q(\tau )=q_{t}(\tau )+q_{s}(\tau ).}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/9e3f8bb053921e9fc9092f0578db13586b211362" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -0.838ex; width:20.592ex; height:2.843ex;" alt="\,\!q(\tau )=q_{t}(\tau )+q_{s}(\tau )."></span></dd></dl>
<p>For a more complete description of how to solve the above equation, see <a href="/wiki/Ordinary_differential_equation#Linear_ODEs_with_constant_coefficients" title="Ordinary differential equation">linear ODEs with constant coefficients</a>.
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Equivalent_systems">Equivalent systems</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Harmonic_oscillator&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: Equivalent systems">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/System_equivalence" title="System equivalence">System equivalence</a></div>
<p>Harmonic oscillators occurring in a number of areas of engineering are equivalent in the sense that their mathematical models are identical (see <a href="#Universal_oscillator_equation">universal oscillator equation</a> above).  Below is a table showing analogous quantities in four harmonic oscillator systems in mechanics and electronics.  If analogous parameters on the same line in the table are given numerically equal values, the behavior of the oscillators—their output waveform, resonant frequency, damping factor, etc.—are the same.
</p>
<table class="wikitable" cellpadding="4" style="background:#F8F8F8;">
<tbody><tr>
<th width="225" align="left">Translational Mechanical
</th>
<th width="225" align="left">Rotational Mechanical
</th>
<th width="225" align="left"><a href="/wiki/RLC_Circuit#Series_RLC_circuit" class="mw-redirect" title="RLC Circuit">Series RLC Circuit</a>
</th>
<th width="225" align="left"><a href="/wiki/RLC_Circuit#Parallel_RLC_circuit" class="mw-redirect" title="RLC Circuit">Parallel RLC Circuit</a>
</th></tr>
